04535nam a22006855i 9780226575421DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018006356  a9780226575421  a(DE-B1597)521357  a(OCoLC)1049974997  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBD460.O74bL38 2018 4aBD460.O74bL38 2019 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a909223  aCC 6600qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17661:1 aLaunay, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSavages, Romans, and Despots :bThinking about Others from Montaigne to Herder /cRobert Launay. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tONE. Maps of Mankind -- tTWO. The World Turned Upside Down: Mandeville -- tTHREE. Between Two Saddles: Montaigne -- tFOUR. Climactic Harmonies: Bodin -- tFIVE. St. Confucius: The Jesuits in China -- tSIX. Distant Relations: The Jesuits in New France -- tSEVEN. Ancients, Moderns, and Others: Fontenelle and Temple -- tEIGHT. The Specter of Despotism: Montesquieu and Voltaire -- tNINE. Savage Critics: Lahontan, Rousseau, and Diderot -- tTEN. From Savagery to Decadence: Ferguson, Millar, and Gibbon -- tELEVEN. Cultural Critique: Herder -- tTWELVE. “Others” Are Good to Think -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the sixteenth to the eighteenth centuries, Europeans struggled to understand their identity in the same way we do as individuals: by comparing themselves to others. In Savages, Romans, and Despots, Robert Launay takes us on a fascinating tour of early modern and modern history in an attempt to untangle how various depictions of “foreign” cultures and civilizations saturated debates about religion, morality, politics, and art. Beginning with Mandeville and Montaigne, and working through Montesquieu, Diderot, Gibbon, Herder, and others, Launay traces how Europeans both admired and disdained unfamiliar societies in their attempts to work through the inner conflicts of their own social worlds. Some of these writers drew caricatures of “savages,” “Oriental despots,” and “ancient” Greeks and Romans. Others earnestly attempted to understand them. But, throughout this history, comparative thinking opened a space for critical reflection. At its worst, such space could give rise to a sense of European superiority. At its best, however, it could prompt awareness of the value of other ways of being in the world. Launay’s masterful survey of some of the Western tradition’s finest minds offers a keen exploration of the genesis of the notion of “civilization,” as well as an engaging portrait of the promises and perils of cross-cultural comparison.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 0aAnthropology-Philosophy. 0aOther (Philosophy) 0aOther (Philosophy). 0aOther minds (Theory of knowledge) 0aOther minds (Theory of knowledge). 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aBritish.  aEnlightenment.  aEuropeans.  aFrench.  aGerman.  aGreeks.  aRomans.  acomparisons.  ahistory of ideas.  asavages and despots.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226575421423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226575421/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles